COCHLEA

cochlea is the bone-housed spiral structure of the inner ear that converts sound into substrate signals
sound waves enter the ear canal, vibrate the eardrum, transmit through three small bones in the middle ear, and arrive at the cochlea where they are sampled by hair cells along a spiral basilar membrane
the cochlea's tonotopic organization (low frequencies at the apex, high frequencies at the base) is preserved all the way to the auditory cortex; this is what allows fadriel to hear pitch

